    <segment id="1" parent="12" relname="circumstance">When it comes to usability of websites and web design,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="20" relname="span"> it is almost impossible to simply 
please everyone.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="contrast">  Some web surfers yearn for animation and pizzazz on sites</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="16" relname="contrast"> while 
others find it distracting and simply superfluous.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="21" relname="span">  There must be a balanced medium</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="11" relname="span"> and 
designers need to seek the means at addressing a balanced site design that is user-
centered</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="14" relname="antithesis"> rather than a company-centered site that might detract visitors from returned 
visits.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="29" relname="span">
They must seek to understand what motivates Web surfers as a group and what they are 
primarily in search of.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="30" relname="span">  The majority of Web surfers are seeking some form of 
information; approximately 90%.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="25" relname="span">  Majority of these users are also in a hurry (arent we 
all) and dont necessarily want to be impeded by a plethora of graphics that utilize 
precious download time.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="24" relname="span">  Web surfers are pretty much over the awe stage of this 
technology and want to move past it to utilize this tool for meaningful use.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="evidence">  They often 
know what they want and want the quickest possible means at retrieving that information 
or product.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="28" relname="span">
Sites that look good superficially but dont necessarily solve problems, which is 
essentially why users surf the web, are deterring using and contradicting good design 
practices according to Barnum (2002).</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="23" relname="span">  The problem, she believes, is that usability isnt 
an automatic process: </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="22" relname="span"> web designs always turn out bad</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="17" relname="unless"> unless project teams make 
certain to apply usability throughout the design process.
</segment>
